first check PATH variable  


check PATH
echo $PATH

/usr/local/bin is most suitable and can be used system wide


To make symbolic link
syntax:

sudo ln -s  <absolute_path_of_ft>  /usr/local/bin/ft

example
sudo ln -s /home/ubuntu/bash/finance_tracker/ft_2 /usr/local/bin/ft

permissions:

sudo chmod +x ft

Example output after symbolic link:

ubuntu@ip-172-31-33-44:~/bash/finance_tracker$ ft
Invalid argument:

Finance Tracker - User Guide
====================================

Usage:
  ft <action> [record]

Actions:
  add    <record>    Add a new record (example: "Chipotle -12.50")
  remove <record>    Remove a record by description
  view               View all records
  clear              Remove all records (confirmation required)
  help               Show this guide

Examples:
  ft add "Starbucks -5.75"
  ft remove "Starbucks -5.75"
  ft view
  ft clear
  ft help




checkk from other users as well

1) create user :
sudo adduser username

2) switch user:
sudo su - username

3) test:
ft #if it works means syslink is working fine


Possible issue fix:
possible error : command not found

check permissions of folder where original ft file is located

let's suppose , ft is stored in

/home/ubuntu/bash/finance_tracker/ft

every folder should be having rx permission for other users.

check permissions of each folder using 
ls -l command

if any folder don't have rx for other give permissions 
using sudo chmod o+rx folder
example :

sudo chmod o+rx /home/ubuntu
sudo chmod o+rx /home/ubuntu/bash
sudo chmod o+rx /home/ubuntu/bash/finance_tracker
sudo chmod o+rx /home/ubuntu/bash/finance_tracker/ft
